diff --git a/README.md b/README.md
index 2fca3136..8a20d1a4 100644
--- a/README.md
+++ b/README.md
@@ -133,6 +133,43 @@ The normal Hive loop is simple: the daemon advances ready tasks, and the TUI is
 
 That is enough to understand what Hive does: it turns a rough idea into durable stage files, then keeps advancing the same task toward code, a pull request, review, and archive. Manual TUI keys still exist for power users who want to steer a specific stage themselves; the happy path is daemon-first. See [wiki/commands/tui.md](wiki/commands/tui.md) for the full dashboard reference.
 
+## Local (non-Docker) install/run
+
+You do not need Docker to run the Hive web UI. `hive setup` brings up the whole
+local mode in one command, against your **real** Hive state — the same tasks
+and repos the TUI drives, no sandbox:
+
+```sh
+hive setup
+```
+
+It runs a preflight (Ruby 3.4+, git, tmux, gh, claude, codex, node/npm, qmd,
+the web bundle, SQLite), bootstraps the deps Hive owns (qmd and the web/ Rails
+bundle), installs the daemon on the same binary as your CLI and enrolls the
+current repo, then installs and starts the web UI at **http://127.0.0.1:4567**.
+A task you create in the TUI shows up in the web UI and the enabled daemon
+runs it automatically — and vice versa.
+
+External agent CLIs (`gh`, `claude`, `codex`) are **diagnosed, never
+auto-installed**: if one is missing or signed out, `hive setup` prints the
+exact fix command (e.g. `gh auth login`, `claude setup-token`) and still exits
+0. Only a too-old Ruby, a refused public bind, or a web bundle that will not
+build are hard failures.
+
+The web tier is a managed service you control like the daemon:
+
+```sh
+hive web                 # foreground (always works, no service needed)
+hive web install         # systemd-user (Linux) / launchd (macOS) unit
+hive web start | stop
+hive web status --json
+```
+
+The default bind is loopback (`127.0.0.1`, no auth). Binding a non-loopback
+address is refused unless you configure the GitHub owner/device-flow claim or
+pass `--unsafe`. The Docker/hivebox image remains a fully supported
+alternative — this mode does not change it.
+
 ## Manage Hive From Telegram in 2 Minutes
 
 Hive can notify you, show the queue, and accept approvals from Telegram. It uses long polling, so there is no webhook, public URL, or tunnel to configure.
